    <fr:title text="Wild initial objects from universal cones › "><fr:link href="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-003B.xml" title="Wild initial objects from universal cones" addr="jms-003B" type="local">Wild initial objects from universal cones</fr:link> › </fr:title>
    <fr:taxon>Proof</fr:taxon>
  </fr:frontmatter>
  <fr:mainmatter>
  <html:p>To show that <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathbf {hom}_{\mathcal {C}}{\mathopen {}\left (I,A\right )\mathclose {}}]]></fr:tex> is contractible, we choose <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\alpha _{A} : \mathbf {hom}_{\mathcal {C}}{\mathopen {}\left (I,A\right )\mathclose {}}]]></fr:tex> as the center of contraction. To identify any <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[f : \mathbf {hom}_{\mathcal {C}}{\mathopen {}\left (I,A\right )\mathclose {}}]]></fr:tex> with <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\alpha _{A}]]></fr:tex>, we use the <fr:link href="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-0039.xml" title="Wild natural transformation" addr="jms-0039" type="local">wild naturality</fr:link> of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[{\Delta  I}\xrightarrow {{\alpha }}{1_{\mathcal {C}}}]]></fr:tex>. In particular, we have an identification <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\alpha _f]]></fr:tex> between <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\alpha _I;f]]></fr:tex> and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[1_{I};\alpha _A]]></fr:tex>. By our assumption that <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\alpha _I=1_{I}]]></fr:tex> and using the <fr:link href="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-0037.xml" title="Wild category" addr="jms-0037" type="local">wild left-unit</fr:link> identifications <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\lambda  f]]></fr:tex> and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\lambda  \alpha _A]]></fr:tex>, we may identify <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[f]]></fr:tex> with <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\alpha _A]]></fr:tex>.</html:p>
</fr:mainmatter>
